Olivia Rodrigo (@oliviarodrigo) knows that getting vaccinated is good 4 u and everyone around u. This week, the artist visited @potus at the @whitehouse to learn more about the importance of getting vaccinated from Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of the US National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases. 

“Whether you’re ready to go back to school, see a concert or visit loved ones, make sure you get vaccinated and do your part,” Olivia says. “YOU have the power to save lives.” 

If you’re 12 years or older, you’re eligible to get vaccinated in the US. To find a vaccination center, go to vaccines.gov and check out our story to see more from Olivia’s special visit. ❤️

Music by @oliviarodrigo

“This one means a lot,” says Tokyo-bound Mexican gymnast Daniel Corral (@danielcorralmx). 🤸‍♂️ 
 
Before stamping his ticket to the 2020 games, the 31-year-old athlete came out of a two-year retirement to begin training for what will be his third and final Olympics. “I’ll be closing a beautiful chapter of my life,” he says. 
 
Keep an eye on Daniel as he flips, swings and leaps into the #Tokyo2020 @olympics. 
 
Reel by @danielcorralmx 
Music by @nashvillemayor

Life in transition ✌️ ⁣
 ⁣
Dancer, content creator and creative director Melissa Crispim Freire (@melycrisp) spent her time during lockdown making mind-boggling videos. “Dance gave me all the skills to create my transition videos,” she says. “It’s just like choreographing the camera. It’s all inspired by musicality and movement.” ⁣
🙃 ⁣
“I keep searching and evolving each time I create a new video,” says Melissa, who is based in London. “I am a very spontaneous creative. I don’t over-analyze. I let it flow, I capture things that are beautiful to my eyes and I play a lot with camera movement.” ⁣
💫 ⁣
Since the start of the pandemic Melissa has been going through her own transition. “I have been a professional dancer for over 15 years, but that is becoming secondary now. I’ve recently directed my first music video, so I am definitely on a new journey — and I am excited about it.” ⁣
 ⁣
Reel by @melycrisp ⁣
Music by @ciara

Spotted: Whitney Peak (@whitneypeak) having an epic New York City summer. 🚕🌇❤️⁣
 ⁣
Meet the 18-year-old actress, who is one of the stars of the new “Gossip Girl” (@gossipgirl) series on @hbomax. While Whitney’s originally from Kampala, Uganda, and spent much of her childhood in Vancouver, British Columbia, she’s sharing her favorite part of summertime in NYC, where the iconic series takes place. ✨⁣
 ⁣
“I love the fashion and the clothing (or should I say, lack of it)” says Whitney. “It’s liberating seeing people comfortable in their skin and individuality. There also somehow always seems to be music playing loud wherever you go, whether it’s a car parked on the sidewalk or next to a skater with a boombox. I didn’t really see things like that in Canada.” 💕⁣
 ⁣
To celebrate the fashion, the music and all things summer (including summer rain storms), head over to our story to see a playlist of songs curated by Whitney. 🗽🎶👗⁣
 ⁣
Photo by @whitneypeak

Deja Foxx (@dejafoxx) is leading thought at the intersection of social justice and social media — and “redefining sisterhood for a new generation.” ⁣
 ⁣
After experiencing homelessness in high school, Deja earned a full-ride scholarship to Columbia University, becoming the first person in her family to go to college. But she felt lost. “I’d always defined community as the people who lived around me, but now I was finding the people who shared my experiences were people I was connecting with online,” says the 21-year-old. ⁣
 ⁣
She founded GenZ Girl Gang (@genzgirlgang) her freshman year from the idea that there is power in our personal networks and that we can use social media as a tool for community building. ⁣
 ⁣
“Our generation faces some of the biggest and most irreversible issues. We need women and femmes at the forefront of our movements,” she says. “All too often women and femmes are taught there can only be one seat at the table that we must compete with each other for. But our generation won’t settle for a seat at the table. We are creating our own.” ⁣
 ⁣
Photo by @dejafoxx

Brazilian skateboarding sensation Pamela Rosa (@pamelarosaskt) is ready to take the skateparks of Tokyo by storm. 🛹⚡️ 
 
Leading up to the Olympic Games, the 21-year-old has rarely gone a day without a skateboard in hand. Training has been nonstop, whether it’s in the gym lifting weights or in the park grinding rails. “I’m most looking forward to representing my country,” says Pamela. 
 
You can expect Pamela to open up her bag of tricks at the #Tokyo2020 @olympics. ✨ 
 
Reel by @pamelarosaskt
Music by @samgellaitry

A day in the life — fairy dream edition 🧚🏼‍♀️💕 
 
“I am obsessed with everything that’s pink and fairy-like. I like to make my life feel like it’s a dream, so I love to play around with my style and looks to convey that,” Lily (@douxfairy). 
 
“When I make Reels I always try to capture the things that bring me joy, like sunsets, flowers, the beach, my style and just anything that makes me feel something. My process on making this reel was thinking of a location that I love, which was Santa Barbara, and recording my day being over there. I love looking back on my videos like that because they always put a smile on my face.” 
 
Take inspiration from Lily and make your own day in the life stitch-together edit on Reels. 
 
Reel by @douxfairy 
Music by @sza

We are dancing into the weekend with BoBo (@gumdorbo_the_caique), a sweet caique parrot and her happy feet. #WeeklyFluff⁣
⁣
Video by @gumdorbo_the_caique

How did BMX freestyle athlete Rim Nakamura (@rimbmx) feel when he qualified for the Olympics? “I got fired up!” he says. 🔥 
 
Not only is Rim competing in the Olympic debut of BMX freestyle, he gets to perform one of his signature tricks, “Big Air,” on the world’s biggest stage in front of his home crowd in Japan. 
 
Catch @rimbmx competing in BMX freestyle at the #Tokyo2020 @olympics. 
 
Reel by @rimbmx 
Music by @anarchyrrr

Although the first song that Audrey Mika (@audreymikaa) posted online was an original composition, it took a steady stream of covers and an iconic pink plastic toy microphone to get her noticed. Then her lo-fi bedroom pop really took off when her track “Y U Gotta B Like That” went viral.⁣
💕⁣
“I still can’t believe to this day that’s the song that’s successful because I made that entire song on my own in my old bedroom,” says the 20-year-old.⁣
💕⁣
“I want my music to be perceived as feeling free and empowered. I don’t open up to a lot of people in person, but for some reason I can be so vulnerable and open in my music,” says Audrey. “At the end of the day music is always going to be there for every emotion. I hope to do that with my own music — to make one person even to not feel alone and feel a sense of security.”⁣
⁣
Photo by @audreymikaa⁣

“I honor my culture today by either expressing it through my makeup looks and headpieces or by talking about it over social media,” says creator Sari-Ella Thaiday (@sarithaiday). She credits her Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander heritage with shaping who she is and providing infinite inspiration.⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
“My grandfathers on both sides of my family would often make headpieces that played a huge role in our culture,” says the 24-year-old. “Their art almost entirely influenced everything I do now as a makeup artist. The creativity is like a skill that’s been passed down.”⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
In that way, Sari’s makeup art both honors her heritage and helps her share her culture with the world. “A lot of people became interested in what I was doing and were able to learn a lot about First Nations people.”⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
Today, Sari shows us a new makeup look inspired by #NAIDOCWeek, a time that celebrates the history, culture and achievements of the First Nations people of Australia.⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
Reel by @sarithaiday ⁣⁣

Hello? 🥰⁣⁣
⁣⁣
“I love using African headwraps and super fun sounds and cool transitions to showcase my looks.” —Folakemi Anike Okesola (@anikesglow)⁣⁣
⁣⁣
“My work celebrates the diversity of makeup, beauty and art in Nigeria. There’s so much talent and creativity here that I feel is overlooked and underrepresented,” says the 21-year-old MUA, who was inspired by fellow Nigerian artist @lindanwaora to create this look.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
“My makeup isn’t just limited to my own face, but when my face is the canvas it’s a lot more comfortable. It’s easier to spend all the time and energy I need and fail and correct mistakes — or even start over. For the Nigerian makeup community, especially upcoming artists, I’d like them to know that about me and to keep working hard, too.” ✨⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Reel by @anikesglow⁣⁣
Music by @yameiionline⁣⁣

There’s no better way to celebrate the tipoff of the 2021 @nba Finals than a ride on @thehoopbus. 🚌 🏀⁣
⁣
Based out of Venice, California, the Hoopbus is a vehicle of change that raises awareness for social justice issues and brings people and communities together through the simple joy of play. “Our mission is to rebuild, empower and amplify communities through basketball,” says Dan Moroni, executive director of Hoopbus, which hosts popup games, rebuilds basketball courts and goes on tours to help break down social barriers.⁣
⁣
In 2020, the 40-foot-long converted school bus with basketball hoops on the front and back drove from Los Angeles to Washington, DC, to participate and lead Black Lives Matter protests across the US. This year the Hoopbus launched the women’s empowerment campaign “We Got Next!” and will be organizing women’s tournaments and partnering with an all-star team of female creators. ⛹️‍♀️ ⭐️⁣
⁣
Check out today’s story as @oflynnstone takes us on a tour of the Hoopbus — and head over to the #NBAHouse all finals long for some 💯 🏀 content.⁣
⁣
Photo of @thehoopbus by @garyland

An ankle injury six months before the Paralympic Games might have spelled disaster for Desi Vila Bargiela (@desivila98). But the subsequent yearlong delay worked in favor of the 23-year-old Spanish Paralympian, who was able to heal and come back stronger than ever. 💪⁣⁣
⁣⁣
“I’m also young and I have a lot of room for improvement, so the extra year has helped me to continue learning and working,” she says.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Keep your eyes peeled for Desi when she competes in the long jump and 100m at the #Tokyo2020 @paralympics. 🏆⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Reel by @desivila98⁣⁣
Music by @dannygokey

“We’re all familiar with the idea of America as the ‘Promised Land,’ but to make sure that holds, it’s crucial that we question who exactly is given access to that promise.” —Nigerian-American creative director and stylist Alexander-Julian (@alexanderjulian)⁣
⁣
Alexander-Julian’s collaborative visual series “The Land of Milk and Honey” (@thelandofmilkandhoney) highlights the stories of immigrant families across the US and dissects the concept of the American dream through stylized photography and representative interpretations of traditional cultural garments.⁣
⁣
“The American dream is a concept that underscores the values of our country that many of our parents and grandparents came to America in search of,” says Alexander-Julian. “But when you have racism and xenophobia becoming commonplace, the validity of that concept comes into question.”⁣
⁣
He hopes the project is a starting place for dialogue. “I believe sharing our perspective or amplifying the perspective of others is our only hope to create a world and an environment where anyone can feel seen, heard and valued.”⁣
⁣
See more from the ongoing series right now on our story. #ShareBlackStories 🖤⁣
⁣
Photos by @alexandersaladrigas, @riotmuse, @dennistejero, @hadadebarro and @a_kid_named_trav

Reach for the treats.

🍡🍡🍡

On today’s #WeeklyFluff, meet Rody, Tino, Goan and Hinako (@rody.tino.tomoko) — a cat pack with purrfect table manners. 😻

Reel by @rody.tino.tomoko

tmw you find perfect harmony 🎼😃🎼

Check out our story rn to see more things that made us smile this week.

Reel by @vanjess
Music by @vanessacarltonactual

Professional surfer Johanne Defay (@johannedefay) is an expert at rolling with whatever comes her way. So when the pandemic hit, the first French female surfer to qualify for the Olympic Games did what she does best — she kept surfing. 🏄‍♀️

“The yearlong delay has been less painful for a new sport like surfing compared to others where you know exactly what to expect,” says Johanne. “I continued to train hard. As surfers, we depend so much on conditions and the waves that we know it’s never the same anyway.”

Catch Johanne riding the waves and competing at the #Tokyo2020 @olympics next month. 🌊

Reel by @johannedefay 
Music by @yurayunita

Amanda Quach (@virghoe_xoxo) found her personal style after years of trying on new trends and thrifting pieces outside of her comfort zone. “Whenever I’m picking out an outfit, I try to be the most funky and vibrant person I can be, which definitely helps in expressing my true self — regardless of how introverted I am,” says the 19-year-old content creator. 
🌼🧡💚 
“Growing up as a plus-sized woman has presented me with countless challenges and obstacles to navigate through while simply trying to achieve the same ambitions as everyone else. Knowing firsthand just how difficult it can get is the reason why advocating for body positivity is so important to me,” says Amanda. 
🧡💚🌼 
“When people see me as a plus-size woman of color living my best life and essentially not letting my disadvantages hold me back, I hope it gives them that confidence to do the same.” 
 
Photos by @virghoe_xoxo

Where do you keep your crystals? ⁣
 ⁣
Bianka Quintanilla-Whye, owner of @bserene.co, which sells hand-held crystals and healing jewelry, suggests keeping them in your car for protection, on your desk for focus and in your bedroom for serenity. “I like wearing crystal necklaces because the energy follows you everywhere,” says Bianka, who is also a yoga teacher and mechanical engineer. “You can never have too many crystals.” 🔮✨ ⁣
 ⁣
Bianka says the movement to shop Black businesses has given a much-needed boost to b.serene. “I am so grateful for the support and increased visibility. Visibility in turn leads to more opportunities for Black-owned businesses,” she says. ⁣
 ⁣
“Our spending habits hold a lot of power, and if we consciously direct dollars towards Black-owned businesses, we have a huge impact that could close the wealth gap, promote entrepreneurial equity and create more empowering opportunities for Black communities.” #BuyBlack ⁣
 ⁣
Videos by @bserene.co

“My goal with making these videos is to make whoever watches them — whether it be one or one million people — feel just 1% better about their day, themselves or their lives.”⁣⁣

“I want everyone who looks at me to feel what I feel: that feeling of freedom,” says 23-year-old women’s world longboard dancing champion Marina Correia (@marinacorreiarr).

“No matter what mood I’m in, longboarding is always an escape and I feel better when I skate. When I’m sad I skate, when I’m happy I skate, when I’m angry I skate,” says Marina, who was born in Cape Verde and moved to the south of France when she was 14.

“I’m proud that I’ve inspired other people to longboard and do what they love, especially Black women because we need more representation and the fact that I’m contributing to that makes me happy.”

22-year-old Japanese musician eill (@_eill_) started singing and composing music on her laptop at age 15 — blending K-pop, J-pop, soul and R&B influences to produce her own unique sound and send the message, “I’m always the protagonist in my life.” ⁣

Since her breakout single “MAKUAKE,” eill has refused to be categorized into a specific genre. “I made this song full of determination to start my own life on my own terms,” she says. But that’s not to say she’s not willing to collaborate. During the pandemic eill worked online with several artists, including Pink Sweat$ and Taeyeon. ⁣

Earlier this year she released her first major label single, “Koko de Iki wo Shite,” a song written as the ending theme for the TV anime “Tokyo Revengers.” “I wrote down what the heroine was feeling,” says eill. “Music can gently convey the true feelings that no one can express. If one day it becomes someone’s light, the darkness will turn into light.” ⁣

Although the 17-year-old creator styles her hair as a way to express herself all year round, June just feels different.⁣
⁣
“Another thing I love doing especially during Pride Month is braiding my hair because I can whip it around and be more free than I ever am,” she says. “Pride Month is the prime to have that feeling.”⁣

“Inspiration comes everywhere for me — sometimes it’s fueled by emotion and sometimes it’s as simple as that skirt would look cute with this shirt. And if it makes me feel like a real rock star, even better.” —Musician and performer Brock Painn (@cheapainn) 
 
Brock doesn’t remember a time not being obsessed with fashion. 
 
“I’d always steal my mom’s heels and makeup and practice for hours walking and trying it all on in hopes that one day I’d be able to navigate it like a pro. I think it’s safe to say my younger self would be proud of me today.” 
 
“I wanna celebrate kids like me, people who feel like they don’t fit in because of what they wear or how they look or how they act,” says Brock. “I always remind myself that it’s best to live your truth freely to inspire others rather than hide in the shadows all your life.”

“I want my work to change the narrative and restore honor to Black fatherhood.” —Entrepreneur and father of three Sean Williams (@sean4real)⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Sean founded the Dad Gang (@thedadgang) five years ago to showcase active Black fathers through positive messages, images and affirmations and debunk the myth that most Black dads are absent or inactive. “My dream is that it not only shatters the negative stereotype of Black dads but empowers all dads to be active dads and live their best dad life,” says Sean.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
“Being an active dad has enhanced my life in so many ways, mostly by allowing me to relive a lot of those fun playful moments that we as adults tend to forget. It’s like I’m living my second childhood with and through my kids.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
To protect Black children, we need to educate them on the realities of the world we’re living in and make them aware of the dangers they can potentially face when they step outside. I do this while also empowering them to love themselves and their differences and above all treating others the way they would want to be treated.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
This Father’s Day, I want to tell my fellow Black dads to stand tall and be proud of how amazing they are. To be able to take care of our families and communities, put smiles on the faces of those that depend on us, to go out into the world and excel in our careers and build legacies and a foundation for future generations to thrive off of — all while still being marginalized, profiled, stereotyped, treated unjustly — is an incredible feat that should not go uncelebrated. We are strong and resilient men of honor. We are dad goals.”⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Photos of @sean4real by @steve__e

At 22 years old, Maya Ghazal (@ghazalmia) is the first female Syrian refugee pilot. In the few short years since she fled her home country of Syria to the UK, she’s accomplished her dream of solo flight. Her next goal is to become a commercial pilot, and bring other women up with her. “I want to use my story and platform to highlight the importance of having more women in aviation,” says Maya. “I feel that when one woman succeeds, we all succeed and we can create a world where young people and females are allowed to flourish and think outside the box without labels to hold them back.”⁣
⁣
As a goodwill ambassador for UNHCR, the UN Refugee Agency (@refugees), Maya advocates for refugees around the globe. “I want to give hope to refugees, as well as other young people and women, that everything is possible. I also use my voice to smash stereotypes about refugees and show that we can be the role models we want to see,” says Maya.  #WorldRefugeeDay⁣
⁣
Photo by @ghazalmia

“Juneteenth is an Independence Day for Black Americans,” says Lynae Vanee (@_lyneezy). “Honoring it is just another step in unlearning American lore and learning exactly how systems exist to marginalize specific groups.”⁣
⁣
Lynae is an Atlanta-based creator, poet and former high school teacher who uses her platform and her master’s degree in African American studies to “spill the tea” on topics that she finds have been ignored or misrepresented.⁣
⁣
“Black people are generally left out of narratives essential to American history,” says Lynae. “Sharing Black stories amplifies Black voices. It grants Black storytellers the autonomy to take up space in rooms not meant for them and imagine worlds others may not have even considered possible.”⁣
⁣
Today, we’re honoring Juneteenth, which commemorates the day — June 19, 1865 — that enslaved African Americans in Texas learned of their freedom. Check out today’s story to learn more. #ShareBlackStories⁣
⁣

“Activism has made me who I am today — resilient, persistent and passionate.” —17-year-old Elijah McKenzie-Jackson (@elijahmckenziejackson)
⁣
Two years ago, Elijah became an organizer with Fridays For Future, a global movement of school strikes to protest the lack of action on the climate crisis. Since then, the UK-based student’s involvement in initiatives and protests — including an expedition into the Amazon rainforest to discuss the safeguarding of its future — has continued to raise awareness of global environmental injustices and the impacts of the climate crisis on marginalized communities as well as ecosystems.⁣
⁣
“The future I am fighting for is not a green world that is built of oppression, but one which embraces diversity, culture and difference which works on the idea of equity. I believe this must be mirrored in the climate movement, giving more space to people who have to shout in comparison to others who can just talk and be heard equally,” says Elijah.⁣
⁣
“Everyone is needed to create change and to achieve climate justice. We all have a voice, it is just finding a way to feel empowered enough to use it. Everyone’s talents, skills and experiences are invaluable and so important to further action within the people and places of power.”

Photo of @elijahmckenziejackson by @harryrosestudio

“It is my hope that the design world evolves to reflect the diversity of the world we live in. Design is as diverse as we are. We need to value that reality.” —Antwaun Sargent (@sirsargent) ✨⁣
⁣
Antwaun is a New York City-based writer and curator who focuses on Black contemporary art and design. He is also the grant committee lead for @design and @brooklynmuseum’s newly launched program, #BlackDesignVisionaries. Through a series of grants and mentorships, the program seeks to uplift aspiring and up-and-coming Black designers who embody the design values of simplicity, craft and inclusivity.⁣
⁣
“Design is fundamental to how we understand the world,” says Antwaun. “Everything in our culture is designed. It can be small, like creating a doodle on a piece of paper, or large, like creating a building. Black artists and designers are often overlooked in those conversations although they have designed communities, buildings, books, fashion and objects that have really changed our experience of the world. To have the opportunity to help shine a light on Black design practice is really an honor and fits in with my work to critically examine Black artistic practice.”⁣
⁣
Learn more about #BlackDesignVisionaries (and get details on how to apply 📬) by heading to @design, and check out a few of @sirsargent’s favorite Black design accounts on our story today.⁣
⁣
#ShareBlackStories⁣
⁣
Photo by @sirsargent

“We are like cheerleaders to the world’s youth.” —ATARASHII GAKKO! (@japan_leaders)

ATARASHII GAKKO! is an outlandish, four-girl progressive Japanese pop group — clad in school uniforms — that blends punk energy with elements of pop, rock, jazz, hip-hop and self-choreographed avant-garde dance in their performances.

Unlike many idol groups, whose personalities, lyrical themes and choreography are polished to perfection, band members Mizyu, Suzuka, Kanon and Rin combine in supercharged exuberance, embrace the weird and do things differently. “We just do things in a way that is natural to us and true to ourselves. We really do wear our hearts on our sleeves.”

ATARASHII GAKKO! translates as ‘New School,’ but the band explains that “symbolically it represents the Seishun [youth] spirit of living your life with open eyes and an open heart at full force. No regrets.”

“We love that our music and performances resonate with a global audience,” they say. “We express our work through the Japanese culture lens but youth energy is universal. We strive to keep surprising you, making you dance and feel the joy of being alive!”

Reel and music by @japan_leaders

⁣
“Exist Loudly is a love letter to my younger self,” says the founder. “It’s a commitment to Black LGBTQ+ young people that there will be spaces for them to just exist, without minimizing their identity to feel safe, loved or cared for.”⁣

“This piece is a reminder to take a few deep breaths and be kind to ourselves, to rest and recuperate.” 💞 —Illustrator and visual artist Sudeepti Tucker (@sudeepti.tucker)⁣
⁣
Sudeepti is based in New Delhi, India, and created this illustration in response to the country's COVID-19 crisis. “We are collectively witnessing a very stressful time and most of us are overwhelmed and exhausted,” she says. “I wanted to show that despite a very present threat outside, our homes remain a safe space where we can blossom and heal.”⁣
⁣
Part of the healing comes from the outpouring of support she's seen between friends and families and even strangers. “While the circumstances that demand this collective courage are sad, it is very heartening that in the face of this continuing crisis, we are standing by each other and helping as much as we can.”⁣

“Whether it’s fashion, makeup, K-pop or even an LGBTQ+ skit, the overall message across all of the content that I create is that you should just have fun, be passionate about what you do and be yourself,” says California-based creator Kevin Ninh, aka @flawlesskevin.⁣
⁣
“Flawless to me doesn’t necessarily mean the absence of flaws, rather it is having those flaws but owning them,” says Kevin. “I hope people are able to learn confidence, feel empowered and practice self-love when they see me living my truth.” ✨🌈🦋⁣
⁣
Kevin is part of Instagram and Facebook’s first-ever Creator Week, which is all about helping creators turn big ideas into full-on careers. See our Creator Week highlight for Live sessions you can tune in to — and follow @creators for more exciting updates from the week. 🤩⁣

“Demand your worth and nothing less.” —Recording artist Fousheé (@fousheelive)

While Fousheé’s journey as a singer-songwriter is informed by her eclectic musical upbringing, her rise to prominence has been complicated, empowering and far from an overnight success.

“My mom introduced me to music, it was always blasting in the house,” says Fousheé. “She was a musician herself, so I think it got passed down in my genes. I used to dance too, and create things a lot — drawings, clothes. But music always held a special place. It was a crucial source of expression for me.

My love of music helped me discover my confidence. I could say anything in a song. It helped me gain patience. Finding the right sounds and ideas takes time, trial and error. The best music happens when you give it space — you can’t force it to happen.”

Fousheé came to prominence recently when she reclaimed her song “Deep End” after an uncredited sample of her voice went viral.

“It was aggravating initially having my voice anonymously being passed around,” she says. “I wanted to connect the dots but didn’t know how. Once that happened, I was relieved. The recognition got me in a lot of doors. It connected me with a world of new people. I think it got people’s attention too. A little mystery makes a person more curious. Since then, I’ve finally gotten the resources and energy to make the music and visuals I’ve been cooking up for a minute. It feels good.”

Reel and music by @fousheelive

“I am a free spirit and love to spread positivity.” —Shalice Ader (@heyshalice)⁣
⁣
The 22-year-old Filipino-American also has alopecia areata, a hair-loss condition that she was diagnosed with at the age of 1.⁣
⁣
“Alopecia and I have a beautiful relationship. I hit rock-bottom mentally because of it, but that allowed me to build mental calluses to become my most confident and happiest self,” says Shalice.⁣
⁣
While growing up, Shalice struggled with periods of depression, stress and anxiety. She suffered bullying and wore wigs and hats to conceal her condition. Today, through her social media presence, she spreads positive energy and openly celebrates her authentic self.⁣
⁣
“I felt alone a lot of the time in my struggle to accept my baldness and I felt that putting myself out there would bring courage to myself and any others who were in a similar situation as I was,” she says. “I hope my photos radiate happiness and confidence to anyone struggling with accepting their appearance. We are all uniquely beautiful and we should embrace that. Love yourself and accept all that you are. You are one of one.”⁣
⁣
Photo by @heyshalice

⁣
This Pride month, Hyeokjin shares some words of inspiration for stepping into the spotlight as our authentic selves. “I hope you do not hide or feel ashamed,” he says, “but love yourself more, hug yourself more, confidently and proudly.”⁣

“I want to inspire people to live in their truth,” says content creator, filmmaker and artist Armiel Chandler (@armielchandler), who uses his platform to educate and spread positivity. 
 
“Growing up, I learned to be in love with myself and who I am. Being creative was my escape from reality to celebrate all the things people thought were flaws but became my strengths. I seek to celebrate Blackness, queerness and body positivity. 
 
All of the content that I try to create is inspired by my younger self — someone who was scared to be themselves and tried to fit in with what he thought was ‘popular.’ My work inspires the little boy and others who felt like they didn’t belong, motivating them to embrace their differences and shine through positivity. 
 
I want to inspire people to love themselves and remind them that they are important, they matter and to not let anyone steal their joy.” 
 
Reel by @armielchandler

“My work is about being limitless, bending reality and creating a powerful and beautiful future for anyone who would like to participate,” says Pea (@peathefeary), an artist and seer who channels Afrofuturism, spirituality, mysticism and human design in their work. ⁣
 ⁣
“I believe that the imagery we see has a direct effect on the future that plays out for us,” says Pea. “My role in this is imagining and creating a vision of Blackness that is paired with fantasy and magic realism. By creating an image of Blackness wrapped in luxury and power, both with my 2D art and the performance art that is my life, I am simultaneously creating a future where this becomes the norm.” ⁣
 ⁣
Pea, who describes themself as “the oracle that you happen to come across in the video game we call life,” also provides affirmation and the tools to foster self-improvement through their podcast and human design readings. ⁣
 ⁣
“Human design is basically a way to look at your own user manual and how you’re designed to work efficiently. It manifests in my work in ways that may not seem obvious externally because its effects in my life had to do more with self-acceptance than anything. Human design has helped me lean further into being OK with being myself and that directly affects the nature and quality of my work. ⁣
 ⁣
I have devoted my life to experimenting with the idea that my experience on this planet is a direct reflection of what I believe is true. So I have spent the last few years of my life proving to myself that by changing the way I think life works I can change my life with minimal physical effort.” ⁣
 ⁣
Art and photo by @peathefeary

Disarming charm. Eclectic vision. Meet Billy Yue (@8illy), the Chinese American creator who is channeling his art through his effervescent personality.

“I went to a really uniform school where there was an academic status quo that every single person followed, and I was always falling behind,” says Billy. “It was a crowd of people who frowned upon creating and art, and I realized I enjoyed doing those things way more than school.”

Billy’s short-form video edits offer up a world of boundless creative possibility and allow him to express himself in unexpected ways through dance, music, drawing and animation.

While Billy’s creative output is pushing culture forward, he feels it’s important to spotlight the API community more widely and positively. “I feel it’s underrepresented, rarely talked about in a positive light or generally appreciated by other communities. Most people don’t know about the community and its culture, so they don’t bother learning or respecting it,” he says.

“The recent wave of hate crimes make me realize that all POC should help each other out with empathy and love because this stuff happens a lot to all of us. I see a lot of people brushing these hate crimes off or even downright refusing to care about them because it’s not within their community — and it’s things like that that make me want to create more so I can have a bigger platform to reach people and teach people about things like this.”

“The next undiscovered Drake or Cardi B is out there somewhere and I want to discover them first. That’s part of the role I play as a producer.” —Atlanta-based producer and musician Kato (@katoproducer) 💫🎶

Kato says there are a few important things he looks for when finding artists to collaborate with. “I look for a certain level of drive and passion, first and foremost. The second thing is some unique quality that makes them special — a story, their voice, their image. It’s often something that you can’t really measure tangibly, it’s just there and you feel it.” 

Despite the challenges of not being able to physically work alongside his favorite collaborators for over a year, Kato’s continued to create by using his own account as a way to invite other musicians to co-produce tracks with him via remixes in Reels, encouraging emerging artists to take a chance and get themselves out there. “It's opened the doors for me to collaborate with people outside of my circle. I’ve discovered new sounds working virtually with other producers, and got fresh ideas from new songwriters and artists all over the world,” he says. “I’ve never had more melody loops and acapellas sitting in my email in my career.”

"My advice to young creators and producers is to try things, especially in those beginning stages. Take all the pressure and expectation out of it and just make the stuff you like. If you like it, chances are other people will too.” ❤️

Check out our story to see some of the musicians Kato’s already discovered via his Remix challenges, and who knows, maybe you’ll be next! 😉✨💕

“I like to dance to fast music, with a fast rope.” — KO-YA (@ko_ya.reg) ⁣
 ⁣
The three-time double Dutch world champion and leader of the REGSTYLE crew describes the frenetic speed and synchronized movements of his performances as a totally immersive experience. “I feel the space inside the rope with all five senses,” says KO-YA, who loves to practice his skills — which can be over 160 beats per minute — on the streets. ⁣

“One of the elements that attracts me to double Dutch is the fact that I can mix with many cultures. I like street culture, hip-hop, dance and sports, and I feel like double Dutch has a lot of these elements.” ⁣

Camaraderie is also a big part of KO-YA’s love for double Dutch. “It allows me to learn about the importance of having a team, since I perform with my friends. I dream of making the world full of smiles and of connecting with lots of people.” ⁣

How far can your dreams take you? Further than you ever imagined. ✨⁣
⁣
Just ask Anthony Ramos (@anthonyramosofficial) and Leslie Grace (@lesliegrace), stars of the upcoming movie musical “In the Heights” (@intheheightsmovie). As two of the film’s central characters, they can relate in more ways than one to the struggles, triumphs and, of course, dreams that their characters have for themselves. ❤️❤️⁣
⁣
“I always dreamt of going off into the world and finding other places that felt like home. And that’s what our movie is about,” says Leslie. “You see so many of our characters follow their dreams and think that they’re in other places, or they find them in the very place that made them up. I know for Anthony and I, a lot of our dreams have been made up and inspired by our love of music.”⁣
⁣
Speaking of music, the film’s melodies highlight and celebrate the authentic stories within the Latinx community — stories of hardship, tradition and dreams becoming fulfilled.⁣
⁣
“Don’t let anyone stop you from going after your dreams wholeheartedly,” says Anthony. “You can do anything you set your mind to if you work hard enough and dream big enough.” 💙💙⁣
⁣
#TakeABreak with these dreamers in a musical extravaganza as they share never-before-heard versions of two original songs from the movie. 🎶💕🎼💫⁣
title: Dreaming to the Highest Heights🎵 with @anthonyramosofficial & @lesliegrace

description:
Kijana “Kiko” Robinson (@kik0xx) first dreamed about starting her own cosmetics line when she graduated high school. “I was just getting serious into makeup, and at that time there wasn’t that much Black-girl-friendly makeup,” says the 23-year-old entrepreneur. “So the thought came to my mind that I should start my own cosmetic line that would be accessible to everyone.” ⁣
 ⁣
Fast forward three years and Kiko’s dream became her reality when her social media followers’ love for her personal makeup looks motivated her to launch her e-commerce business Kik0xxstensions (@kik0xxstensions). ⁣
 ⁣
Kiko is known for her colorful handmade, cruelty-free eyelash extensions and eyeliner with an aesthetic that she says “seeks to celebrate being true to yourself and spreading positive vibes.” ⁣
 ⁣
“The message I'd like to send through my work is to be carefree, strong and do what makes you happy,” says Kiko. “It’s important to support Black businesses because we’re able to create more visibility, representation and jobs for the Black community.” ⁣
 ⁣
Photos by @kik0xx

“The possibilities are infinite,” says creative director and 3D artist Antoni Tudisco (@antonitudisco).⁣
⁣
The Filipino-Italian’s constantly evolving digital imagery seamlessly blends surrealism and reality and seemingly knows no boundaries. “I hope for my audience to feel confused with what’s real and what’s digital. I want them to be surprised with what they see,” he says. “I always present them with something new and that they’ve never seen before or ever expected to see. Something unforgettable.”⁣
⁣
Antoni’s collaboration with fashion designer Ding Yun Zhang (@dingyun_zhang) is a marriage made in utopia: a series of stills and videos that blend Antoni’s hybrid figures wearing exaggerated renderings of Ding’s futuristic oversized puffer jackets within fantastic landscapes.⁣
⁣
“I have always been fashion-oriented since I could remember. And now I’m trying to create my own 3D fashion world. I would love to bring the 3D textures and looks I digitally create into tactile existence one day,” says Antoni.⁣
⁣
As always with Antoni the future is now — he recently started the clothing brand @tudisco.studio.⁣
⁣
Illustrations by @antonitudisco

“Music is the only way I can express myself, totally and truly,” says 20-year-old Paravi Das (@pxrxvi). “I like to say there’s a way to find passion in any song, but it becomes a different sort of magic when you can make a song your own,” explains the singer-songwriter who has recently seen her cover versions go viral and also makes original music.

“Like many children of immigrants, as proud as I am of my culture and heritage, I don’t feel I completely belong to India, and I don’t feel I completely belong to America. I find it easier to feel that sense of grounding when I choose to honor both sides of my being, rather than pretend the other doesn’t exist.

The API community is so often overlooked, especially when it comes to entertainment and music. The things I loved most in life — singing, art, acting, performing — never loved me back, because I never saw someone at the top of these industries that looked like me.
Acknowledging and celebrating unrecognized voices can allow us to make beautiful things. There’s so much more to us — so much more beauty, talent, love, culture and authenticity. Just take a second for a closer look.”

This month, we’re celebrating #APIHeritageMonth by sharing creative voices from the community. #RethinkOurInfluence

Reel and music by @pxrxvi

Dog overboard.⁣
⁣
On today’s #WeeklyFluff, meet Ben and Tim (@bigbentinytim) — two rescue BFFs who despite their differences in size and personality, have a relationship that’s going just swimmingly.⁣
⁣
Video by @bigbentinytim

Now THIS is how you hit the right key. 🎹⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Check out our story right now for more things from this week that are music to our ears. 🎶⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Reel by @musteranatole

Ever wonder how prom started? 🕺🎊🎶
Comedian Lonnie Marts IIV (@lonnieiiv) breaks down the origin story. 😂😂

“My prom experience was pretty standard. I was a weirdo in a Hawaiian shirt running around, hyping everybody up. And I think I did a really good job — like, I would want to hang out with me at prom again,” says Lonnie, who describes his comedy as quirky, optimistic and thoughtful.

“I’m an optimist so I look at a lot of things like, ‘How can we have the most fun with this? How can we make this something that everyone will enjoy and want to be a part of?’ I do that with my content, my audience and my community too — I love involving people and bringing everybody together to just have a great time.”

Putting his humor aside, Lonnie recognizes that many proms this year may still look or feel different from proms of years past, but he has advice on keeping a positive outlook. “If you’re missing out on something, it’s OK to be sad about it. Cry about it — but then pick your head up, get with some good people who know how to be imaginative and get excited about doing what you can do and make it the best darn time you’ve ever had.” 💛❤️

Reel by @lonnieiiv featuring @jenningsbrower

For fashion creator and stylist Lexson Millington (@lexsonator), coming up with a 🔥 color scheme 🔥 runs in the fam.

“Throughout my childhood, my mother would style me for church on Sunday,” says the 23-year-old. “Now I realize that she really set the tone for how I put together an outfit. Color coordination is such a huge part of my life because of her. She’s the real inspiration behind my style.”

Reel by @lexsonator
Music by @kaytranada

“I think one of the most beautiful things that we can give to one another is our vulnerability.” 💕

Introducing Vancouver, Canada-based singer/songwriter Jessia (@jessiamusic) and her latest hit “I’m Not Pretty,” a song that started as a form of personal therapy for the musician and has since become a far-reaching anthem for self-acceptance and body positivity.
🎶 💖 🎶

“I feel like the lyrics have helped me,” says Jessia. “I am the most confident I’ve ever been in my body and I love the person that I look at in the mirror every morning. I don't think I ever felt that way before ‘I’m Not Pretty.’ I also feel like I’m just the messenger of this song, and this song is so much bigger than just me as an artist.”

In theme with #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth, the message of Jessia’s song aims to inspire people to let go of the need for validation from others and to love themselves fully and freely.

“Ain’t nobody got time for social comparisons,” says Jessia. “Just do you and just rock it. Do exactly what you want to do and honestly it’s going to work out so much better than trying to be someone else. Building that relationship with yourself where you’re 100% comfortable with who you are is a really, really beautiful thing.”

For more resources from mental health experts and creators, check out our Guide on the ways to combat social comparison. And to hear more from Jessia, check out our story now! ✨✨

Reel by @jessiamusic
Music by @jessiamusic

“My freestyle riding represents who I am. It is an extension of my personality and I use it to improvise through the world,” says professional bike athlete Brad Simms (@brad_simms).⁣
⁣
Brad was introduced to BMX at age 11 by his uncle. “Since then I have been privileged enough to ride my bike in 100+ countries, learn multiple languages, broaden my global perspective and make friends all around the world. I could not have done it without the bike.⁣
⁣
Freedom of expression is my favorite part about riding BMX. The process of connecting dots that never existed is a feeling that never grows old. You are constantly having to reassess your thinking, because of the mental agility it demands.⁣
⁣
My technique and trick selection are different at this stage of my career. I search for places to do tricks people think are impossible or unique. Jumping over stuff and riding on walls are my favorite things to do now.⁣
⁣
The streets are the best for my style of riding as I’m not confined to one course like I might be in competitions. When I pedal around the city, I don’t know who or what I will run into. The unknown is what keeps me going back day after day. The streets are raw, gritty and unforgiving so you have to always be alert.”⁣
⁣
Video of @brad_simms by @drewpickles

Darci Adele Shepard-Mobbs (@darciadele) and Mia Knights (@miaxalexis) represent the idyllic nature of their long-term relationship through a magical lens inspired by the Renaissance, 19th century English paintings and the folklore of fairies and elves.⁣
⁣
“We like to think the world we have created to be shown by these photos is one of complete content, happiness and calm, since that’s how we feel around one another,” explain the 18-year-olds who live in Norfolk, England.⁣
⁣
“We want to convey to people that it’s OK to wish for things, and that nobody should ever tell you that you can’t have something. We both used to believe that we would never be able to find the kind of love we now share, and that we weren’t even allowed to want it.⁣
⁣
We want to inspire the people that see the fairy tale life we live in to believe that it’s not just a wish, and that we are real people with insecurities and imperfections who worked as individuals to believe that we are worthy of love, as is everyone in the LGBTQ+ community if they want it.⁣
⁣
The best thing about being together is the knowledge that whatever we experience as individuals in life, good or bad, exciting or scary, we are going to have a best friend there to experience it at the same time.”⁣
⁣
Photo by @darciadele and @miaxalexis

Kim Saira’s (@kimsaira) art serves as both a creative healing mechanism for her own mental health and as a tool to support the API community. ⁣
 ⁣
“All of my work revolves around Asian American advocacy, and for telling my story through my experiences, growing up as an Asian American immigrant,” says the Filipina American artist. ⁣
 ⁣
“The anti-Asian hate crimes are no doubt triggering and terrifying. It’s also brought so many different communities together in a time of collective healing. It’s given me hope and strength that through the power of advocacy and uniting, we will get through this together. ⁣
 ⁣
One huge way the API community has been misunderstood is that we are a monolith and that we are all the same, which is incredibly untrue. I want my community and the world to know that API influence consists of so many different people coming from different cultures and backgrounds, and we all have an important role to play for diverse API representation.” ⁣
 ⁣
This month, we’re celebrating #APIHeritageMonth by sharing creative voices from the community. #RethinkOurInfluence ⁣
 ⁣
Art by @kimsaira

“My status as a professional athlete doesn’t exclude me from racism, discrimination, sexism or homophobia. The minute I take that jersey off, I am a Black, bisexual woman in America and as Malcolm X once said, '“The most unprotected person in America is the Black woman.” —Tasha Cloud (@t__cloud9)

The 2021 @wnba season got underway this week and for the @washmystics point guard it marked the first time she has laced up for a game in over a year. Tasha opted out of the 2020 season in order to pursue social justice reform and use her platform for something far bigger than her sport.

“It was the hardest decision for me thus far in my career,” says Tasha. “But I understood that this moment in time was much bigger than myself and my career. I’ve been given this God-given platform to be a voice for the voiceless. If I didn’t use my voice, I’d be doing a disservice to a lot of people that look like me. I wanted to be on the frontlines; not only in spaces that hard dialogues and decisions were being made, but in the community, at marches and at protests.”

Heading into the new season, Tasha is confident her work as an activist and athlete will be championed by her league both on and off the court. “The WNBA is constantly pushing boundaries and progressing the needle forward. We are consistently at the forefront of every social issue.”

#ShareBlackStories 🖤 #SeeMe

Photo of @t__cloud9 by @washmystics

High School diploma ✅
Summer plans in order ✅
Bags packed for college ✅

All that’s left are those unpredictable send-offs and goodbyes — and we all know how those can go. 😭 😬 😘 18-year-old content creator Matt Taylor (@mattheperson) can relate. “I often get inspiration for my videos from social interactions,” says Matt. “This video is very much inspired by people that I have been surrounded by.”

Reel by @mattheperson

This little piggy. 🐷⁣
⁣
On today’s #WeeklyFluff, meet Kyojuro (@kyojuro_micropig) — a fresh-faced micro pig who is ready to roll.⁣
⁣
Photo by @kyojuro_micropig

Paint it. Mix it. Match it. 🎨

Check out our story for more colorful creations, fun videos and other things that made us smile this week. 🙂

Reel by @fritzdoesart_

“I slowly learned that it’s OK to take breaks and enjoy the journey rather than stressing about the destination,” says Yasmine Sahid (@yasmine_sahid) when recalling her life post-graduation. “Life isn’t all about grinding, but also enjoying hobbies and trying new things.” 😉 ✨

The 24-year-old actress and content creator’s videos are largely based on feelings of nostalgia. “They’re mainly inspired by my childhood or cringey scenarios that a lot of people can relate to. Sometimes an idea pops in my head and I write down the scenarios and pick out the funniest jokes. Other times I get writer’s block and I sit and just list things that I used to do, listen to, watch, etc.”

This graduation season, Yasmine is sharing some timely advice. “No one knows what they’re doing. No matter how much someone acts like they know, they don’t. So take it easy on yourself.” ❤️

Reel by @yasmine_sahid 
Music by @ajrbrothers

Virgo. Sagittarius. Gemini. Leo. No matter what your zodiac sign may be, if you’re a member of the Class of 2021 it’s time to party! 👏 🎉 🎓

While the lectures and assignments may be complete, there’s still plenty of personal, post-graduation work to do. Fear not, Mari (@astrologybymari) has you covered. The 25-year-old astrologist provides horoscope readings for all of life’s ups and downs straight from the seat of his car.

His advice for graduates everywhere? “I hope they go where their hearts tell them to go and not where society tells them to go. Their gut instincts are everything,” explains Mari. “If they want it a little easier, I would recommend they look into their zodiac signs as a form of direction. Graduation is one of the biggest achievements, but it’s still just the beginning of something more!”

Reel by @astrologybymari

“Human beatbox” Shogo Kai, aka SHOW-GO (@showgoxkaix), brings his distinctive audio tones to his art, which mixes tempos and powerful beats with only the raw pure sound of the human voice. ⁣
 ⁣
“A major theme is searching for the limits of musical expression within my own flesh and blood,” says the 21-year-old student. “When I make a beatbox tune, it feels more like I have this melody or rhythm that falls into place all at once, rather than me composing it little by little.” ⁣
 ⁣
SHOW-GO, who released his debut album last year, learned his craft by watching online videos starting at the age of 14 before honing his skills at beatbox battles. He also channels his Japanese culture to extend his self-expression beyond his music to his personal fashion. ⁣
 ⁣
“Since beatboxing is not mechanical, the sound can be uneven, and it also includes some noise, but I think that is a strength of beatboxing,” he says. ⁣
⁣
Video and music by @showgoxkaix

UK climate activist and student Dominique Palmer (@domipalmer) became passionate about the climate crisis when she became more aware of its inequitable impact on people.⁣
⁣
“I saw how communities of color were disproportionately facing air pollution, such as my area in London, as well as communities across the world who are already facing impacts that threaten water, food security, air quality, health and lives,” says Dominique, 21, who works on organizing climate strikes and actions, including Fridays for Future International and Climate Live.⁣
⁣
“Justice is key. This means acknowledging systemic issues that cause disproportionate impacts of the crisis. Black Lives Matter has brought the issue of justice more forefront in the environmental movement. Racial justice and climate justice are inseparable due to the historic and continuing impacts of racism, colonialism and inequality on the crisis. The movement needs to be more inclusive, have a deeper understanding of interconnected systemic issues. It needs to be a platform for our voices and genuinely listen to us, not tokenize or speak for us.⁣
⁣
I really want to inspire people to join the movement. Black environmentalists are not well represented in the movement, but we are definitely here. The image of an environmentalist has typically excluded us, and even now intersectional activism that recognizes the importance of equity in climate solutions is slowly being brought to the forefront, but there is a lot of work to do.”⁣
⁣
Photo by @domipalmer

“I’m a Muslim Palestinian-Filipino, born and raised in Texas, who loves to share the richness of my faith and heritage with the world.” —Subhi Taha (@subhi.taha)

Subhi is known for the videos he posts on his account @itsmesubhi, which show the everyday moments that make his culture unique. “The main goal with my content has always been to hopefully help normalize Muslims,” he says. “When someone claims Islam, there are so many negative stereotypes that come with it, and I believe that stems from little to no exposure to us. Hopefully by taking up space in the digital world, Muslim creators can help give folks insight to our beautiful faith.”

Subhi is honoring Eid al-Fitr, or the end of Ramadan, which feels especially important to him this year. “The concept of life right now is so fragile; I can’t help but value the basics. My faith, my family, my community and just being a good energy in people’s lives.”

This month, we’re sharing voices from those observing #Ramadan. Share your own moments of everyday kindness and good with the hashtag #MonthOfGood ✨❤️ 💫 ⁣ 

Reel by @subhi.taha

“I honor my heritage by not shrinking myself, by becoming the most expansive and truthful version of my creative self,” says Korean American artist Leena Cho (@leena_cho).

Leena’s experimental and playful multidisciplinary artistic practice extends from traditional painting and songwriting to MUA.

“Makeup might be thought of as something you put on to mask yourself, to hide your flaws. But to me it’s the most vulnerable form of self-expression. It’s not just my drawings and paintings that I’m putting out, it’s also my face. I hope seeing a Korean American who doesn’t fit the Eurocentric beauty standards confidently using their face to express their creativity feels empowering to those who also feel like they don’t fit those beauty standards.

To reclaim API’s influence in shaping culture means challenging the stereotypes and the idea that we are a monolith. It means taking up space as my authentic self, honoring the cultures that have influenced me and adding complexity to the representation of my community.”

This month, we’re celebrating #APIHeritageMonth by sharing creative voices from the community. #RethinkOurInfluence

Reel by @leena_cho
Music by @danielaandrade

This mama’s got moves! (And her son does too.) 🤩🥰️⁣
⁣
For the Verona, Italy-based mother-son duo, dance has always been a way of connecting with one another. “It is a privilege to be able to share the passion for dance and dancing together. It makes me feel good, the best feeling ever,” says Paola Manghisi (@paola_manghisi), who has been dancing with her son Lorenzo (@lorenzo_brock_) since he was 7 years old.⁣
⁣
“My favorite thing about my mother is the relationship we have and the care she has towards me, both in terms of personal and artistic growth,” says Lorenzo. “I feel very lucky and privileged to be able to share all this with her.” 💕⁣
⁣
Whether you’re a new mom, an empty-nester, a hopeful mom-to-be or thinking about your own mom, we hope these two can bring joy, comfort and a smile to brighten your day.⁣
⁣
Happy #MothersDay to Paola and all those celebrating, whatever your story may be. 💐⁣
⁣
Reel by @lorenzo_brock_ and @paola_manghisi⁣
Music by @madconofficial featuring @raydaltonmusic

Pretty please?⁣
⁣
On today’s #WeeklyFluff, meet Wadsworth (@waddywaves) — a demanding domestic short-hair cat who begs whenever and at whatever he wants.⁣
⁣
“People always ask how we trained Waddy to beg,” says his human Natasha. “We didn’t really teach him. He started doing it on his own, but we encouraged him to continue doing it and now he does it all the time.”⁣
⁣
Video by @waddywaves

Don’t get it twisted. 🪀🌪💫 We have some more fun things to share with you, right now on our story.

Reel by @yoyo_mack8
Music by New Edition

V. retro. Creator Justin Yi (@justinyi_) uses a “super ancient camcorder” to make nostalgia-tinged videos with a little bit of the unexpected. 📹 🙃 
 
“A while back, I made my first camcorder video and instantly fell in love with the feeling it gave me,” says the 21-year-old. “My favorite part is figuring out how I’m going to DIY the concepts I think of. It’s like a little challenge each time.” 
 
Ultimately, Justin hopes that by combining his unique style and sense of humor, his videos will make people feel better. 
 
“It can help people escape from the reality we live in,” he says. “Even if it’s just for a few moments or barely cracking a smile, it still means a lot.” 
 
Reel by @justinyi_ 
Music by @jackstauber

Outside the ring: introverted 🌼 ⁣
 ⁣
Inside the ring: firecracker 💥 ⁣
 ⁣
“I might look like a timid girl whom you might not even bat an eye at,” says Nor Diana (@nordianapw), the world’s first hijab-wearing pro wrestler. But when she’s performing? “I transform into my alter ego, Phoenix.” ⁣
 ⁣
“People like me don’t get booked often due to the way we look and dress, but once I became viral, I broke the barriers and people were starting to book me more often,” says the 21-year-old from Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. ⁣
 ⁣
Sometimes it isn’t practical for Nor to wear the hijab when she’s performing because wrestling is so physical. “But I made sure I found a way to make it practical and not be a barrier for doing something that I love while holding true to my beliefs,” she says. ⁣
 ⁣
Her beliefs include the celebration of Ramadan. “I feel like Ramadan is that one time of that month where most people do more good than usual. And more good is ultimately better.” ⁣
 ⁣
This month, we’re sharing voices from those observing #Ramadan. Share your own moments of everyday kindness and good with the hashtag #MonthOfGood ✨❤️ 💫 ⁣ ⁣
 ⁣
Photo by @nordianapw

“There’s so much power in being you.” ❤️ 
 
Okulaja (@okulaja_) makes music with a message to inspire. “When people become a little bit more sympathetic towards one another, the world can change for the better,” says the 18-year-old student, rapper and anti-bullying advocate. 
 
Okulaja uses his voice in support of the underrepresented and to speak out on issues he’s passionate about. “I care deeply in inspiring other young people and empowering them to believe in themselves and deal with bullying. Mental health is something that we all need to look after, but most of the time forget to. I feel like I can use my music as a gentle reminder to people that you need to look after yourself too. We need to ask ourselves ‘Am I OK?’ sometimes too.” 
 
Reel by @okulaja_

Fashion forward. Slayden Ader (@slayd3n) finds freedom of expression through his personal style. “I am totally valid to wear whatever I want,” says the 17-year-old fashion creator who was raised in Hawaii. “My style makes me feel unique in a way where I can share my creativity and personality through clothing.

When I was younger, I never saw people within mainstream media who looked like me or had the same experiences as me, so it really inspired me to branch out and do something different. I want to inspire other Southeast Asian Americans to be themselves and not be confined to the media’s underrepresentation of our experiences and identities.

It is important to celebrate #APIHeritageMonth to show appreciation for our culture and beliefs — and shed light and acknowledge that we as Asians still struggle with racism and discrimination every day. It is a month to unite the Asian American community, and to feel proud of who we are — and to remember our history and heritage and how far we’ve come.”

This month, we're celebrating #APIHeritageMonth by sharing creative voices from the community. #RethinkOurInfluence

Reel by @slayd3n

She’s a Boss.⁣
On today’s #WeeklyFluff, meet Rowdy (@rowdy_dachshund), a fearless skateboarding miniature long-haired dachshund living her best life and spreading good vibes on the streets of Los Angeles. 🔥⁣
⁣
Video by @rowdy_dachshund

10 seconds is all it takes for TOTAL CHAOS. 🙃

To see more memes that made us smile this week, check out our story rn.

Reel by @lourdasprec

Football fans rejoice! The 2021 @nfl draft kicks off today and this year’s class of draft prospects brings some serious talent to the field. 🏈 👏 👀⁣
⁣
Former North Dakota State University quarterback Trey Lance (@trey.lance) is ready for the show. “I’ve been playing football for as long as I can remember,” says Trey, whose father taught him to play at a young age. “I’m preparing for the draft and the year ahead by training, both mentally and physically, to be ready to go when I get to my new city.”⁣
⁣
Today on our story, join Trey and a few fellow @nfl hopefuls as they quiz our audience in a fun game of “true or false.” 🧐⁣
⁣
Photo of @trey.lance by @uhohdino

“I want to make content that celebrates breaking the mold,” says 19-year-old integrated digital media and computer science student Alexis Williams (@alexisdenisew).⁣
⁣
“My journey in STEM has not been easy in the slightest. I always like to emphasize that because there are still so many strides to be made to ensure that STEM is an equitable field for everyone regardless of gender, race, sexuality or any other identity markers.”⁣
⁣
Alexis started making Reels to reflect her experience and to connect with others who have found themselves dealing with being a part of an underrepresented group within the STEM field. She also combines her passions for creativity and computer science with activism and social justice.⁣
⁣
“I was really emotional after the events of May last summer; I spent many days mourning the death of George Floyd. But afterwards I was just itching to get involved. I wondered how I could possibly join the fight in the middle of a global pandemic.” So Alexis turned to coding and created the Black Lives Matter resource toolkit, PB-Resources.⁣
⁣
“I now understand the importance of the space that I fill as a Black, Latina, queer woman in STEM. I bring a perspective underrepresented in this space, and the programs I create directly reflect that.”⁣
⁣
Photo by @alexisdenisew

“We want to be a part of creating an outdoors and an outdoor industry where all are welcome,” says Jahmicah and Heather Dawes, owners of Slim Pickins Outfitters (@spoutfitter), the first Black-owned independent outdoor retail store in the United States. “We want our sons and our nieces to be able to enjoy nature without the fear of if they are welcome in it.”⁣
⁣
Jahmicah and Heather opened their shop in Stephenville, Texas, in 2017 and remain focused on their mission to diversify the outdoors and spread positivity, despite the roller coaster of 2020. “The past year was very difficult for our small business, as it was for so many. Our revenue was down and we had a new baby,” says Jahmicah. But with the help of a short documentary film, a successful online fundraising campaign and the kindness and support of the wider outdoor community, the doors of Slim Pickins Outfitters have stayed open for business.⁣
⁣
When they’re not greeting customers in the store, you can find Jahmicah and Heather planting flowers and veggies in their garden, taking walks in their neighborhood or picnicking wherever they can fit their blanket. “We never leave home without it,” says Heather. “With kids you never know when someone is going to need a nap, a snack or a change, so we have to have a soft place to land!”⁣
⁣
On today’s story, follow along as the @spoutfitter family shares a few tips and must-have items for an awesome outdoor adventure.⁣
⁣
#ShareBlackStories⁣
⁣
Photo of @spoutfitter by @wondercamp.co

“The goal of my videos is to share my humor and experience and bring joy to both myself and others.” —Seattle-based software engineer and creator Jiayang Li (@plumsojuyang). ⁣
 ⁣
Jiayang began making his relatable videos after graduating college when the pandemic hit. “I was just stuck home waiting to start my full-time job, so I started to create content and post it online out of boredom,” says Jiayang, who was born in China and immigrated to the US in high school. ⁣
 ⁣
“A lot of my humor is self-deprecating, but I do sometimes post content on a current topic that is relevant to me. I try to educate people about my culture and history or give others my perspective on the current situation or issues. ⁣
 ⁣
The racial hate crimes against Asians makes me scared and sad at the same time. I am glad that I have a platform that I can bring greater awareness to my community about current events in a manner that is both easy to digest and relatable.” ⁣
 ⁣
Reel by @plumsojuyang

Let’s get vaccinated ❤️⁣
⁣
Designer Thanh Evan Nguyen (@thanhdesigns) made this illustration for World Immunization Week in the lively style he’s known for. “For me, nature imagery, expressive typography, adorable characters and vibrant colors are universally appreciated. They have always resonated with me as a creative to use and spread my messages of positivity, unity and hope.”⁣
⁣
This time, his message is about the importance of COVID-19 vaccines so that “together we can end this global pandemic and move forward to a better future.”⁣
⁣
For info about COVID-19 vaccine safety and staying safe, check out our story and the COVID-19 Information Center at our link in bio.⁣
⁣
Art by @thanhdesigns

“Double dose of dopeness.” ✨💫⁣⁣
⁣⁣
That’s what you get with Sakinah and Zakiyyah Rahman (@aint.afraid) — twins who share positive messages through their music. “Our music is to tell people you’re already everything you’ll ever need, so love yourself and grow from there.” 💓⁣⁣
⁣⁣
That positivity extends to Ramadan, which they’re celebrating this month. “If life is a race, Ramadan is a pit stop. It’s a month of recharging your soul, reconnecting to the most valuable things in life and getting focused.”⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Watch them perform a song they created about this special time.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
This month, we’re sharing voices from those observing #Ramadan. Share your own moments of everyday kindness and good with the hashtag #MonthOfGood ✨❤️ 💫 ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Reel and music by @aint.afraid

We asked 9-year-old Alan Kim (@official.alankim) what his dream movie would be to write, produce and star in… and this is the trailer. 🎬

You may know him as the breakout star of “Minari” (@minarimovie), but Hollywood newcomer Alan Kim is just getting started taking the film world by storm. In this exclusive trailer to his latest make-believe cinematic masterpiece he’s calling “The Search,” Alan sets off on an epic journey to rescue his best friend (and adorable puppy) Cream who’s been stolen by an evil magician.

“Cream’s dream finally came true: him being a star,” says Alan of his original screenplay.

But the dream doesn’t end there. While we get to enjoy a sneak peek at the movie of Alan’s imagination, he’ll be experiencing another dream fulfilled as he attends his first #Oscars, where “Minari” is nominated for six @theacademy awards. Tune in tonight on @abcnetwork.

Now shhh! The trailer is starting! 🤫🍿
title: Alan Kim’s Dream Movie: The Trailer

“Getting involved in environmental action isn’t about being perfect, it’s about just doing what you can.” —Environmental communicator Summer Dean (@climatediva)

Today on IGTV, listen to Summer, along with environmental and Indigenous rights defender Helena Gualinga (@helenagualinga) and @kidsagainstpalstic co-founders Amy and Ella Meek, discuss the most urgent environmental issues facing the planet today. They also share some everyday things you can do to make a difference.

Despite all the challenges facing the planet, these activists remain hopeful. “It gives me a lot of comfort knowing that all of the solutions we need are in nature,” says Summer. “We just need to come together and figure out how to make that happen.” #EarthDay 🌍
title: #EarthDay Convo with @climatediva, @kidsagainstplastic and @helenagualinga

description:
For Indigenous environmental and human rights defender Helena Gualinga (@helenagualinga), the climate crisis is literally in her backyard. “Last year, as the first wave of the pandemic was hitting Ecuador, my community faced floods of unprecedented magnitudes, destroying schools, bridges, crops and washing away people’s homes,” says Helena, 19, who is a member of the Kichwa community of the Sarayaku. “People were left without homes and secure food sources for months, and a year later we still have not recovered completely. This is a result of a combination of climate change and deforestation.”⁣
⁣
Environmental activism has always been a part of Helena’s life. “When I was very young, my community was threatened by oil companies and immediately the people of my community decided to resist,” she says. “So it’s always been there because it’s about defending our lands, our waters, our home.”⁣
⁣
This #EarthDay, Helena is hopeful. “I feel so privileged how I grew up in the Amazon. Seeing the children today doing all things I used to do as a child, like running around the forest, climbing enormous trees, sometimes I think, why is this even possible? It’s possible because my people fought for it. And that gives me hope — that work is giving happiness to those children, and I really want that to continue.” 🌎⁣
⁣
Photo of @helenagualinga by @martinaorska

“For a long time, there was this set idea of what an environmentalist was, and people of color didn’t really see themselves in that narrative,” says 23-year-old environmental communicator Summer Dean (@climatediva). “Indigenous communities and communities of color are the original creators of sustainability, and we have lived in reciprocal ways with the earth for thousands of years. A lot of the trendy sustainability terms that we see in today’s culture can be traced back to the cultural traditions passed down through communities of color.”

Summer, who lives in Los Angeles, believes that environmentalism needs to be more inclusive. “It doesn’t matter how ‘green’ you are or how much you know about climate change, you have a role to play in this movement. Sustainability isn’t always about innovations and new technologies, sometimes it’s just about empowering communities of color and following their lead.”

This #EarthDay, Summer advocates for avoiding fast fashion trends, which are inherently unsustainable. “I try to buy things with the mindset of quality over quantity, so when I do buy things they will last me forever,” she says. “Practice gratitude for the things in your life, and remember that you are worthy and enough just the way you are without any products at all.” 🌎

Reel by @climatediva
Music by @taylaparx

“My art is messy, imaginative and personal,” says Salwa Rahman (@urgalsal_). “It’s art therapy for me.” ⁣
 ⁣
“My approach to makeup artistry is one about accepting the mistakes and appreciating the journey,” says the Muslim British-Bangladeshi creator who sees similarities between her art and the month of Ramadan. ⁣
 ⁣
Like this swan look, for example. “Swans can depict grace and trust as well as linking to inner beauty and self-love. These are all key concepts that are encouraged to be practiced in full during the month of Ramadan. It’s a time of letting go of ego and moving gently over the waters of life with compassion and kindness.” ⁣
 ⁣
This month, we’re sharing voices from those observing #Ramadan. Share your own moments of everyday kindness and good with the hashtag #MonthOfGood ✨❤️ 💫 ⁣
 ⁣
Photo and video by @urgalsal_

Amy and Ella Meek have taken the plastic problem into their own hands. Over the past five years, the 17- and 15-year-old UK-based sisters and founders of @kidsagainstplastic have picked up nearly 100,000 pieces of single-use plastic — and they developed an app so people around the world can join their effort.⁣
⁣
“Every year that we delay action against climate change or against plastic pollution or against any other environmental crises facing our planet is another year that people’s lives are negatively impacted or put at risk,” says Amy. “As people who are going to grow up to this future, that’s an alarming concept.”⁣
⁣
This #EarthDay, Amy and Ella advocate for reducing the “Big 4” plastic polluters: plastic bottles, cups and lids, straws and bags. “These are convenience items that we often use every day with little thought, and they’re in the top 10 of ocean plastic pollutants for a reason—we use a lot of them!” says Amy, who tries to use reusable alternatives for the Big 4 in her life. “Obviously simple changes like these alone aren’t going to solve the plastic waste crisis, but they are great stepping stones to bigger action.” 🌍⁣
⁣
Photo by @kidsagainstplastic

Ramadan Mubarak from Settat, Morocco ✨ ⁣
 ⁣
That’s where filmmaker and photographer El Mostafa Irgui (@elmostafa_irgui) is celebrating this special time with the people closest to him. “Since Muslims are all fasting together, there is a strong sense of community during Ramadan. Families that rarely share a meal break their fast together at the same time each day and many mosques organize a communal iftar, which is especially beneficial for people who live alone.” ⁣
 ⁣
Family and home also serve as inspiration for the vintage, minimalist fashion looks El Mostafa’s known to rock. “When I was around 10 years old, I remember my father taking me to the store and buying me clothes every month. He’s my role model and my inspiration — in most of my Instagram posts, I wear his clothes,” he says, adding that the city of Settat is what got him into the vintage style. “What’s most important about the images I make is trying to leave the Moroccan touch and present my culture to the world.” ⁣
 ⁣
This month, we’re sharing voices from those observing #Ramadan. Share your own moments of everyday kindness and good with the hashtag #MonthOfGood ❤️ 💫 ⁣
 ⁣
Photos of @elmostafa_irgui by @ridabzioui, @othmanekniksi and @bousga

Most days, you can catch Tasneem Elaidy (@tasneemelaidy) working on her music from her home in Cairo, Egypt — especially after an overnight viral hit. This month, the 20-year-old musician and student is also focused on Ramadan. ⁣
 ⁣
“Ramadan is a month of joy, love and warmth,” she says. “I have heard a lot of stereotypes that Ramadan is a month where Muslims suffer a lot and I can assure you that we don’t.” ⁣
 ⁣
Tasneem loves honoring this special time with people around the world. “The only thing that makes me cry on the spot is when I am in a place where there are a bunch of people doing the same thing at the same time together,” she says. “The idea that all the Muslims all around are praying for one God is just beautiful. It makes me feel so connected to my religion and roots.” ⁣
 ⁣
This month, we’re sharing voices from those observing #Ramadan. Share your own moments of everyday kindness and good with the hashtag #MonthOfGood ✨❤️ 💫 ⁣
 ⁣
Photo of @tasneemelaidy by @aliaa_m.jpg

“The world that we’re fighting for is one where our strength is not determined by how much suffering we endure. Let it also be determined by how much joy we can hold,” says Janaya Future Khan (@janayathefuture), a writer based in Los Angeles.⁣
⁣
As part of their Sunday Sermon series, Janaya goes live each week to spark necessary conversations about racial justice. Their most recent Sermon focused on the importance of uniting all movements, like #BlackLivesMatter and #StopAsianHate.⁣
⁣
“Our silence allows bigotry to grow in power,” they say. “We have to push past our fear and into our collective power. It’s important that we start to take responsibility for issues that don’t specifically impact the communities we’re from.”⁣
⁣
For almost a year, Sunday Sermon has become a source of motivation and support for the community, and for Janaya, as well.⁣
⁣
“When I started Sermon, it was for other people,” they say. “But the community and care I get from that space every week is grounding and beautiful, and forces me to work through whatever I’m going through that week to show up with care and integrity. It’s a really profound thing to be a part of something where however you feel, and whatever you look like, folks will accept you exactly as you are.”⁣
⁣
Janaya goes live on their account on Sundays at noon Pacific. #ShareBlackStories⁣
⁣
Videos by @janayathefuture
