“I am looking for the painterly component in digital animation,” says artist Dirk Koy (@dirkkoy), who runs a motion design and experimental film studio. ⁣
 ⁣
Dirk embraces different technologies, including drones, 3D animation, photogrammetry, AR and VR, to create his experimental digital images. ⁣
 ⁣
“I am interested in exploring a shape and working out different ways it can be represented and perceived,” he says. “I really love the edgy shapes of this beautiful car. And I was super curious about what digital manipulations I could do with it. I thought it would be fantastic to develop a great 80s sound to it. I realized that the pitch bend distortion of the sound fits very well with the visual distortion.” ⁣
 ⁣
Video by @dirkkoy

POV: you’re someone who studies diseases for a living. As an epidemiologist, Jessica Malaty Rivera (@jessicamalatyrivera) knows a lot about COVID-19 and the vaccines to fight it.

“Being fearful of the virus, the data, and even the vaccines is a completely normal response. I want people to know that after spending a year analyzing devastating COVID-19 data, that these vaccines not only exceeded our expectations for efficacy, they are also very safe. The benefits of vaccination far outweigh any possible risk. This virus is cruel. And we finally have a tool in our toolkit to beat it.”

That tool also means the end is in sight. “This pandemic will not last forever. The most important things people can do is to keep your risk low. That means: wear your masks, practice physical distancing, avoid indoor/large gatherings and get vaccinated as soon as it’s your turn.”

For more reliable info about COVID-19 and vaccine safety, check out the COVID-19 Information Center at our link in bio.

Reel by @jessicamalatyrivera

⁣
“It has always been difficult to be taken seriously as a female skateboarder,” explains Nora. “I always wanted to be seen the same way and taken as seriously as the men are. I wanted to travel and create products like the men. I wanted to be put on the same pedestal as male professional skaters.⁣
⁣
I hope watching me skate inspires you to go out and do something that makes you feel good.”⁣

“I feel colors. I like comfortable compositions and balanced energy,” says Beijing-born, London-based fashion design student Yang Yue (@a1jewel). “I specialize in bio textiles [materials grown from live microorganisms] and do makeup and other face decorations as a hobby. Makeup is my ASMR. It’s just a way for me to release pressure.”⁣
⁣
Her inkblot-like, abstract MUA looks (@a1jewel0310) draw heavily on her Chinese heritage. “It is embedded in my aesthetic,” she explains. Whether Yang takes inspiration from Beijing opera grease paint makeup, bronze vessels from the ancient Chinese Warring States period, mythical creatures or real-life animals, all these references have a home in her bold and beautiful universe.⁣

For comedian Jes Tom (@jesthekid), #TransDayOfVisibility is about trans and nonbinary people sharing their experiences and celebrating each other. 🏳️‍⚧️⁣
 ⁣

 ⁣
“Trans people are extremely diverse, and we have different needs depending on different factors. However, we all deserve free access to healthcare.”⁣
 ⁣
For resources and ways to help, check out @trevorproject and @glaad. #ShareWithPride⁣

“I’m just a girl from DC with a passion and vision to tell inclusive stories that will hopefully inspire other audacious visionaries to dream big and go after what they want.” —17-year-old actress, producer and filmmaker Lexi Underwood (@officiallexiunderwood)⁣
⁣
Lexi is living out her dream and creating space for others to do the same. This year, she’s one of the nominees at the NAACP Image Awards (@naacpimageawards), which celebrate outstanding achievements and performances in the Black community, an honor that Lexi takes serious pride in as she dedicates herself to amplifying Black stories.⁣
⁣
“If you can’t see it, you can’t be it. We normalize our stories by sharing them. When we fill these spaces and lean into our brilliance, Black stories are no longer reduced to ethnic experiences, anomalies or urban myths of mythical creatures.⁣
⁣
Our joyous, complex stories take center stage as a normalized way of life, connected to universal experiences that ultimately connect us to the human experience, where we find that we are more alike than we are different.”⁣
⁣
Today on our story, Lexi highlights some of the women who inspire her every day.⁣
#ShareBlackStories 🖤⁣
⁣
Photo by @officiallexiunderwood

“I’ve always wanted to stand out,” says 18-year-old Leo Mandella (@gullyguyleo). “I have never wanted to blend in with the so-called ‘normal.’” As long as Leo can remember, he’s expressed himself everyday through fashion.⁣
⁣
“The way I put a look together is by thinking of everything. Everything could include where you’re going, who you’re seeing, what the environment you’re going to looks like.⁣
⁣
I like to match my color palettes in an outfit to my environment, as this makes it so much more effective. Always add your own personal twist on this.⁣
⁣
My main tip is to feel comfortable. Never force yourself into something because you think it looks best, because believe me, people can notice when you aren’t comfortable in your own drip.”⁣
⁣
Photo by @gullyguyleo

“Ink is a historical tool for storytelling, and the strokes of the ball pen are to me what words are to any other storyteller,” explains Oscar Ukonu (@oscarukonu), whose detailed, hyper-realistic portraits are drawn with an everyday ballpoint pen. ⁣
 ⁣
“My style is a practice in time and patience,” says the Lagos-based artist, who works approximately 300 hours on a single piece. “My work celebrates the diversity in the strength and richness of the African lived experiences and realities, which in many ways has been lost to the repetitive and underrepresented concept of ‘'being Black’ in this part of the world. ⁣
 ⁣
Portraying African identities in my work is also an attempt to empower Black people in diaspora and shine light on the diverse ways of knowing and being for Black people in general.” ⁣
 ⁣
Art and Video by @oscarukonu

“I would like to spread the message of hope and resilience by sharing my peoples’ stories,” says 19-year-old advocate and multimedia artist Yang (@indigenousiconyang). “As young people, we are often left out, doubted and ignored, but I want you to know: we are sacred, we are the dreams of our ancestors. We are the change we need in this world.” ⁣
 ⁣
Yang began her advocacy journey at age 15 and three years later was leading thousands of young people in the 2019 global climate strike at the state capitol in New Mexico. ⁣
 ⁣
“As Indigenous people, we have never been given any opportunities to share our stories and identities,” says Yang, who is Diné and Chicana from Dinétah, the traditional homeland of the Navajo tribe.⁣
⁣
“Historically, my community, facing environmental racism, colonization, discrimination has been sacrificed for the development of the economy. I realized at a young age I had an important and sacred obligation to my people, to speak, make art and bring awareness to these social and environmental injustices. Because at the end of the day, we have to.” ⁣
 ⁣
Photo of @indigenousiconyang by @charleykingphotography

“Black women get the short end of the stick, so to be as successful as I am, it means everything to me.” —University of South Carolina student athlete Aliyah Boston (@aliyah.boston)⁣
⁣
Today, the sophomore leads her team (@gamecockwbb) into @ncaawbb #MarchMadness. Her hard work and dedication paid off in a No. 1 seed position for her team, plus Aliyah was named a first-team All-American.⁣
⁣
“I hope that I’m able to inspire younger Black girls to have the confidence to play whatever sport they want,” explains Aliyah, who fights for equality on and off the court. “Push through every obstacle, because it’s not going to be easy.”⁣
⁣
#ShareBlackStories 🖤 #SeeMe⁣
⁣
Photo of @aliyah.boston by @kevindliles for @sportsillustrated and @sifullframe

“I want to encourage people to move, dance, live out loud and surpass the struggles they once felt were too monumental.” —Photographer, stylist and art director Grace Bukunmi (@bukunmigrace)⁣
💕⁣
For the last four years, Grace focused her lens on fine arts, specifically ballet. In her project “Danze Noir,” Grace challenges antiquated stereotypes and cultural barriers while amplifying and celebrating diverse voices. Dancers such as Coco Lavine (@cocolavine) and Alexis Turner (@sparkle4every1) invited Grace to document their craft and talk about race, representation and visibility.⁣
⁣
“I was greatly inspired by their dedication to excellence, their resilience against inequalities and their perseverance in a grueling field. It’s super easy to give up when gatekeepers place doubts on your career and many in the world question your abilities due to your skin color. There have been times when I have wanted to give up, yet these women and others motivated me in how they’ve navigated their careers in the midst of racism and adversity.⁣
⁣
I hope that the project inspires others to keep hope alive, to find inspiration within tasks and situations that they find most difficult, and lastly, to recognize their own internal and external strengths,” says Grace.⁣
⁣
#ShareBlackStories⁣
⁣
Photos of @sparkle4every1 and @cocolavine by @bukunmigrace

“I started with just me in my bedroom on an acoustic guitar,” says genre-hopping artist Beatrice Laus, aka Beabadoobee (@radvxz).⁣
⁣
Originally from the Philippines, the singer-songwriter picked up a violin at age 5, but the guitar didn’t come into the picture until she was 17. “I was kicked out of school and started to get a bit down about everything,” explains Bea, now 20. “My dad bought me an acoustic guitar, and I started to write songs.”⁣
⁣
“Coffee” was the very first song Bea ever wrote. She posted the lo-fi debut for fun, and things took off. Fast. The song landed Bea a record deal, and the viral hit had a second life when it was sampled by Canadian rapper Powfu, extending to literally billions of plays. 🤯 Late last year, Bea released “Fake It Flowers,” her very first album.⁣
⁣
“I’ve grown into writing bigger songs with much louder full band instrumentations that touch on a lot of different moods. It all felt very personal to me, like a diary.”⁣
⁣
Photo by @radvxz

For 22-year-old Brian Trujillo (@anewspecimen), his artwork is his happy place. “I lose all focus on the worldly problems I have,” explains Brian, whose colorful, meditative graphics show emanations of auras and affirmations.⁣

“I love color and playing around with different combinations to create ethereal visuals. People who see auras say they are accurate, but I just make what I envision it could look like if we could all see auras and energy; it’s creative interpretation on my part.⁣
⁣
If my work eases people’s anxiety or mental health with color — even if it’s just temporary — that’s part of my purpose.”⁣
⁣
For more positive creative vibes and affirmations, check out today’s story. ✨⁣

But for me, it’s a process that I really enjoy.” ⁣

Listeners around the world clearly enjoy it, too. This year, the four-time Grammy Award (@recordingacademy) winner is nominated in three categories, including “Album of the Year.” But Jacob’s focus remains on the creative process. 🎶💫 ⁣

“Asking me to change my hair is like asking me to erase my Blackness.” —18-year-old ⁣antiracism and social justice activist Zulaikha Patel (@zulaikhapatel_) ⁣
⁣
After struggling with racial bullying and low self-esteem in primary school, Zulaikha started her first day at an all-girls school in Pretoria, South Africa, at age 13 confident and hopeful: “My Afro was flourishing and my curls were popping,” she says. “But from the get-go, overt racism was thrown in my face.” ⁣
⁣
Zulaikha was scolded by teachers for speaking with friends in her native tongue at the formerly all-white school. And she was told her hair didn’t comply with school policy. “They said it had to be tied at the nape of your neck. Think about that: When you’re African, and you have not chemically straightened your hair, that is impossible. I have yet to see the day that I have tied my hair at the nape of my neck.” ⁣
⁣
Zulaikha, along with a dozen classmates, protested at school and began the #StopRacismAtPretoriaGirlsHigh movement on social media, sparking a nationwide conversation about racism and cultural discrimination in schools. ⁣

“It’s a never-ending moment,” says Zulaikha. “It represented something bigger. It gave Black women voices in other movements.”

@confidencecodegirls shares stories about #GirlsOfAction, including Zulaikha, and encourages women to live their most confident life. #WomensHistoryMonth ⁣
⁣
Photo by @zulaikhapatel_

In the summer of 2017, Jamie Margolin’s (@jamie_s_margolin) hometown of Seattle was enveloped in smoke due to nearby wildfires. “Breathing the air hurt,” she says. “I decided that the local climate organizing I had been doing in my community had to be taken to the next level — there needed to be mass mobilizations of youth all over the world standing up for our lives and our futures.” ⁣
 ⁣
So Jamie, who’s now 19, co-founded Zero Hour, the international youth climate justice organization that leads marches in cities around the world. She continues to organize campaigns, strikes and protests to fight for urgent climate action. ⁣
 ⁣
Jamie honors #WomensHistoryMonth because women’s stories are often erased from the narrative of history. “So many movements and achievements in history were created and led by women, but the history books retell everything from a purely male perspective where the women are passive in our own stories,” she says. “We have to reverse the wrongs of history and properly highlight and appreciate the work women do for our world.” ⁣
 ⁣
@confidencecodegirls shares stories about #GirlsOfAction, including Jamie, and encourages women to live their most confident life. ⁣
 ⁣
Photo of @jamie_s_margolin by @bojnovak

Period poverty, the inability to afford menstruation supplies, isn’t a female issue — it’s a human rights and education issue, says 21-year-old Amika George (@amikageorge). ⁣
 ⁣
“When you are too poor to put food on the table or heat your home, the chances are that you are struggling to afford period products too,” says Amika, who started @freeperiods four years ago and successfully campaigned the British government to provide free period products to every school in England. ⁣
 ⁣
“Period poverty is a gendered inequality that only impacts people who menstruate. This isn’t something we opt into; it’s a natural biological process. We can all do more to break the stigma and shame bound up in periods. They’re not something we should be silent and embarrassed about. ⁣
 ⁣
They are normal, and we need to all talk more about periods to normalize the discourse around menstruation if we want to create a more equal society for all.” ⁣
 ⁣
@confidencecodegirls shares stories about #GirlsOfAction, including Amika, and encourages women to live their most confident life. #WomensHistoryMonth ⁣
 ⁣
Photo by @amikageorge

Indian entrepreneur and dancer Lekhinee Desai (@lekhinee26) says her family’s handmade sustainable fashion brand, The Indian Ethnic Co. (@theindianethnicco), puts a contemporary twist on traditional women’s clothing — allowing a woman to “just be while she goes about conquering her day.”⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Growing up, Lekhinee’s mom, Hetal Desai, never liked the dresses she found in stores for Lekhinee and her sister, so she made them herself. Fast-forward to 2016, Lekhinee was pursuing her MBA, her sister was studying medicine and Hetal was looking for new things to occupy her time. “I nudged her to get back to what she does best — making the most beautiful clothes,” says Lekhinee.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
So the mother-daughter team started an “experiment” — an online clothing business from their home. Today, they have three offices in Mumbai and work with more than 100 master artisans, shipping saris and other products to customers around the globe.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Plus, they started a dancing movement on Instagram: “When I started wearing and dancing in a sari, it helped me connect to the history of womanhood of this oldest and most versatile form of Indian clothing,” says Lekhinee. “And it inspired so many millennials to go all out in a sari, because suddenly saris had started looking ‘cool.’ We have a tribe of happy women, dancing their hearts out on the internet in a sari. What better way to connect to your womanhood⁣ than this?!” #internationalwomensday ⁣
⁣
Reel of @lekhinee26, Twaraa Desai, @apurvadani and @charvib by @adityabhansali_⁣

Stacie Denetsosie (@navajodarling) reconciles grief and enacts ceremony through her writing. “As shared in my poem ‘Universe Diné Born Woman,’ it’s a Diné (Navajo) tradition to bury your infant’s umbilical cord to keep your child connected to the earth wherever they may roam.

I consider this land like my own mother. In that sense, I am connected to all the women before me, because they have done this same tradition for their children,” says Stacie, who is Diné and lives in Utah.

“The Diné peoples are a matriarchal tribe. I think it’s important to remember what the women in our lives and those throughout history have had to sacrifice in order for us to be where we are today.”

“In a world that wants to change us, it’s a radical act of resistance to love ourselves for exactly who we are," says actor, fitness instructor and self-proclaimed “lover of life” James Rose (@jamesissmiling), who has recovered from disordered eating. “It’s not about looking in the mirror and enjoying what you see; it’s about internalizing that you are wholly worthy beyond any reflection.”

James struggled with society’s expectation of masculinity, while being lauded for their femininity, and never fully identifying with either one. “My disordered eating was, in many ways, an attempt to manipulate my body to conform to both of these gendered expectations. The expectations I was attempting to conform to were never mine.”

For James, a community that uplifts and celebrates you is key to any kind of recovery. “Positive community isn’t about surrounding yourself with people who say nice things to you. It’s filling your circle with folks who love you enough to call you in, to educate you, to let you cry on their shoulder, to cheer you on and allow you to do the same for them.”

It’s #NEDAwareness Week. In collaboration with @neda, Instagram is supporting people who may be affected by negative body image or an eating disorder. Learn more from the link in our bio.

JoJo Watson’s (@jojoslipzz) advocacy work is all about building online communities. His journey started after JoJo shared a video about his experience growing up in a children’s residential care home.⁣
⁣
“I was alone, and I wanted to connect with someone to see if anybody else out there was going through what I was going through,” says 21-year-old JoJo. “From that video, I was able to create a family of care leavers and current care residents.” He continues to work with the care community and also advocates for plus-sized men of color through his Instagram account @plussizemenmatter.⁣
⁣
“My work celebrates men of all shapes and sizes to boost their body confidence and empower. Seeing people connect and interact and message one another is so special. And it shows how crucially the space that I’ve created was needed. Sometimes the hyper-masculinity in men affects us to not talk about real deep issues such as mental health and embrace ourselves.⁣
⁣
My work seeks to challenge that stigma with an open, honest conversation with males. From body positivity to self-worth to self-love to mental health, we challenge to break down those barriers and change them forever.”⁣

Songwriter and producer Tima Diakite (@timalikesmusic) is known for the catchy tunes she creates in her bedroom studio, and she made this one for Black History Month.⁣
⁣
“Knowing that this rhythm and this style of singing and the soul — it comes from pain, it comes from speaking the truth,” she says. “That’s what brings me Black joy, is to know that though this came from hurt, we turned this into magic.”⁣
⁣
“I love Black people. I love us. I do.”⁣
⁣
See Tima spread more Black joy on today’s IGTV.⁣ #ShareBlackStories 🖤⁣

Reel by @timalikesmusic

Comedic R&B. Dream soul. New jack swing. Quiet storm. And a little bit of chaos.

That’s how Tima Diakite (@timalikesmusic) describes the music she produces about relatable, funny everyday moments.

“I love that feeling of waking up to R&B radio Sunday morning knowing you had to clean or waking up to gospel music. Whenever I’m creating music, I try to recapture that vibe.

How did I feel at my aunt’s wedding? How did I feel at my graduation cookout? I try to capture that because the Black experience, it’s like no other. I’m telling you, it’s a vibe.”

This Black History Month, we continue to #ShareBlackStories and celebrate Black joy in all its glory. 🖤
title: My Black Joy with @timalikesmusic

description:
“When I am at my best mental, physical and spiritual health everything around me falls into alignment,” says 20-year-old holistic herbalist Cassandra Pressley (@cassandrathegreat_). “That alignment is something every being has a right to experience.⁣
⁣
I seek to convey the message of Black beauty and happiness. I celebrate different kinds of beauty and lifestyles that may not fit into mainstream ideals. We all have a mission on this planet to create the most harmonious and balanced life for ourselves we can, which spills over in our interactions with others and spreads harmony.⁣
⁣
I just want people to know that you are your own healer. Look inside of yourself for your answers. Meditate and sit with yourself daily, even if for only three minutes. Read up on the human body and the things we can do to turn it into a mean, green illness-beating machine. The work is a lifelong journey that you have to choose to take on.”⁣
⁣
#ThisWeekOnInstagram⁣
⁣
Video by @cassandrathegreat_

“I am committed to radically imagining the possibilities of what transformative, soulful and decolonized education can look like,” says founder and director of the Free Black University (@freeblackuni) Melz Owusu (@melzdot).⁣
⁣
“The Free Black Uni is about more than just a Black education. It’s about holding this idea that the world can actually change. I am channeling and learning from Black people in history who have done work that changed the passage of time. Their thoughts were seen as inconceivable. They were seen as radical. They were seen by so many as wrong, but they still pushed ahead.⁣
⁣
Being nonbinary and trans, I can see the ways the world has failed us all and recognize that I can change anything. It’s helped me push beyond every boundary and every limited possibility that I thought existed. I explain my gender as I’m in the constant creation of it every single day. In the same way, I’m in a constant creation of the world around me every single day.⁣
⁣
Impossibility is such an important aspect of my work. Radical possibilities are possible, and we don’t just have to fix this little pot of racism. We don’t have to fix this little part of classism or this little part of transphobia. The whole system in and of itself can be different and we need to work together to create that difference.⁣
⁣
#ThisWeekOnInstagram⁣
⁣
Photo by @melzdot
